I would look to use the life cycle hooks that Angular 8 will offer you over trying to build a directive that evaluates on creation, I think this is the recommended way now. As well this will ensure it is not running multiple times.

Whatever logic you wanted to put inside this directive can be done in the `ngOnInit()` life cycle hook which is fired at the creation of a component before the HTML is drawn.


    class ExampleClass implements OnInit {
      public ngOnInit() {
        // put here your initialising logic you wanted in the html.
      }
    }


If its important the HTML is rendered first you can use `ngAfterViewInit()`, this is a function that is called after the view is attached ( HTML exists ). Very similar looking to use.

    class ExampleClass implements AfterViewInit {
      public ngAfterViewInit() {
        // put here your initialising logic you wanted in the html, for after view loaded.
      }
    }

Worth reading about the difference lifecycle hooks and how to leverage them, from the [docs](https://angular.io/guide/lifecycle-hooks).

